Wash and dry all produce. Halve and peel @red onion{1}(halved and peeled); very thinly slice one half and finely chop other half. Core, deseed, and dice @poblano pepper{1}(diced into ½-inch pieces). Roughly chop @cilantro{¼%oz}(roughly chopped). Dice @roma tomato{1}(diced). Halve @lime{1}(halved); cut one half into wedges.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine sliced onion, @white wine vinegar{5%tsp}, @sugar{2%tsp}, @salt{½%tsp}, and @water{1%tbsp}. Stir until sugar and salt are mostly dissolved. Set aside, stirring occasionally, until ready to serve.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @ground pork{10%oz} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Transfer to a #plate{} and set aside.

Heat another drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp} in same pan over medium-high heat. Add poblano and chopped onion; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Return pork to pan along with @fajita spice blend{1%tbsp}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, half the @tomato paste{1.5%oz}, and @water{¼%cup}. Cook, scraping up any browned bits from bottom of pan, until mixture is thickened and saucy, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Use all the tomato paste for 4 servings, and increase water to ⅓ cup if doubling.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{2%tbsp}, a squeeze of juice from lime half to taste, and a pinch of @chipotle powder{1%tsp} (add more to taste if you like things spicy). Stir in @water{1%tsp} 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with salt and pepper. Wrap @flour tortillas{6} in damp #paper towels{} and microwave until warm and pliable, ~{30%seconds}.

Divide filling, tomato, @Monterey Jack cheese{¼%cup}, cilantro, pickled onion, and crema between tortillas. Serve with lime wedges on the side.

> TIP: Alternatively, you can put everything in individual serving bowls and let everyone assemble their own tacos.